# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lanolin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] It is synthesized from lathosterol by the enzyme lathosterol oxidase (lathosterol 5-desaturase).
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] This is the next-to-last step of cholesterol biosynthesis.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Defective synthesis results in the human inherited disorder lathosterolosis resembling Smith–Lemli–Opitz syndrome.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Mice where this gene has been deleted lose the ability to increase vitamin D3 in the blood following UV exposure of the skin.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The skin consists of two primary layers: an inner layer, the dermis, comprising largely connective tissue, and an outer, thinner epidermis.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The thickness of the epidermis ranges from 0.04 mm to greater than 0.6 mm.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The epidermis comprises five *strata*; from outer to inner, they are the stratum corneum, stratum lucidum, stratum granulosum, stratum spinosum, and stratum basale.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The highest concentrations of 7-dehydrocholesterol are found in the epidermal layer of skin—specifically in the stratum basale and stratum spinosum.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The production of pre-vitamin D3 is, therefore, greatest in these two layers.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Synthesis of pre-vitamin D3 in the skin involves UVB radiation, which effectively penetrates only the epidermal layers of skin.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] 7-Dehydrocholesterol absorbs UV light most effectively at wavelengths between 295 and 300 nm and, thus, the production of vitamin D3 will occur primarily at those wavelengths.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] The two most important factors that govern the generation of pre-vitamin D3 are the quantity (intensity) and quality (appropriate wavelength) of the UVB irradiation reaching the 7-dehydrocholesterol deep in the stratum basale and stratum spinosum.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Light-emitting diodes (LEDs) can be used to produce the radiation.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Another important consideration is the quantity of 7-dehydrocholesterol present in the skin.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] Under normal circumstances, ample quantities of 7-dehydrocholesterol (about 25–50 μg/cm2 of skin) are available in the stratum spinosum and stratum basale of human skin to meet the body's vitamin D requirements.
[src:lanolin/7-dehydrocholesterol] 7-DHC insufficiency has been proposed as an alternate cause for Vitamin D deficiency.
[src:lanolin/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:lanolin/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:lanolin/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:lanolin/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:lanolin/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:lanolin/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:lanolin/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:lanolin/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:lanolin/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:lanolin/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:lanolin/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:lanolin/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:lanolin/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:lanolin/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:lanolin/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:lanolin/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:lanolin/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:lanolin/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:lanolin/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:lanolin/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:lanolin/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:lanolin/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:lanolin/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:lanolin/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:lanolin/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:lanolin/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:lanolin/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:lanolin/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:lanolin/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:lanolin/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:lanolin/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:lanolin/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:lanolin/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:lanolin/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:lanolin/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:lanolin/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:lanolin/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:lanolin/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:lanolin/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:lanolin/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:lanolin/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:lanolin/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:lanolin/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:lanolin/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:lanolin/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:lanolin/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:lanolin/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:lanolin/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:lanolin/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:lanolin/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:lanolin/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:lanolin/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:lanolin/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:lanolin/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:lanolin/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:lanolin/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:lanolin/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:lanolin/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:lanolin/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:lanolin/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:lanolin/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:lanolin/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:lanolin/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:lanolin/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:lanolin/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:lanolin/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:lanolin/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:lanolin/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:lanolin/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:lanolin/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:lanolin/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:lanolin/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:lanolin/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:lanolin/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:lanolin/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:lanolin/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:lanolin/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:lanolin/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:lanolin/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:lanolin/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:lanolin/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:lanolin/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:lanolin/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:lanolin/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:lanolin/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:lanolin/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:lanolin/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:lanolin/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:lanolin/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:lanolin/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:lanolin/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:lanolin/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:lanolin/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:lanolin/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:lanolin/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:lanolin/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:lanolin/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:lanolin/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:lanolin/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:lanolin/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:lanolin/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:lanolin/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:lanolin/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:lanolin/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:lanolin/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:lanolin/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:lanolin/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:lanolin/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:lanolin/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:lanolin/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:lanolin/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:lanolin/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:lanolin/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:lanolin/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:lanolin/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:lanolin/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:lanolin/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:lanolin/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:lanolin/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:lanolin/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:lanolin/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:lanolin/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:lanolin/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:lanolin/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:lanolin/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:lanolin/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:lanolin/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:lanolin/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:lanolin/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:lanolin/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:lanolin/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:lanolin/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:lanolin/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:lanolin/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:lanolin/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:lanolin/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:lanolin/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:lanolin/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:lanolin/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:lanolin/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:lanolin/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:lanolin/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:lanolin/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:lanolin/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:lanolin/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:lanolin/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:lanolin/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:lanolin/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:lanolin/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:lanolin/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:lanolin/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:lanolin/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:lanolin/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:lanolin/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:lanolin/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:lanolin/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:lanolin/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:lanolin/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:lanolin/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:lanolin/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:lanolin/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:lanolin/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:lanolin/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:lanolin/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:lanolin/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:lanolin/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:lanolin/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:lanolin/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:lanolin/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:lanolin/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:lanolin/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:lanolin/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:lanolin/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:lanolin/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:lanolin/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:lanolin/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:lanolin/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:lanolin/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:lanolin/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:lanolin/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] Both *acidity regulator* and *pH control agent* can be used interchangeably.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] In the context of food-safe substances, however, *acidity regulator* is typically used over *pH control agent*.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] Below is a list of substances commonly used as acidity regulators.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] When used in food additives, they may instead be known by their E number.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] Acidity regulators usually have an E number between 200 and 399, depending on their use case.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] Food-based applications of acidity regulators are used to keep pH stable, as an incorrect pH can result in bacteria growth.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] They can also be used as a food preservative by means of acidification, which prevents bacteria growth altogether, or as a way to enhance the flavor and/or texture of a food or drink.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] Acidity regulators differ from acidulants, which are often acidic but are added to confer sour flavors.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] They are not intended to stabilize the food, although that can be a collateral benefit.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] pH control agents are used in fracturing fluids to keep its fluid chemistry consistent, as many of its additives (such as gel polymers) require it to stay at a constant pH range.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] Without proper pH control, the variability can cause the liquid to destabilize, potentially destroying equipment (via corrosion) and making fracture propagation less efficient.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] In industrial plants (namely water treatment plants), pH control agents are used to correct the pH of incoming fluids, and in some cases assist in the disinfection of those fluids.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] An unstable pH can lead to the corrosion or scaling of equipment.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] The most common chemicals used to adjust pH in industrial plants are sulfuric acid and sodium hydroxide.
[src:lanolin/acidity-regulator] In the fishkeeping hobby, pH control agents may be used to keep the pH within a range suitable for the plants and animals living in the enclosure, especially in cases where the carbonate hardness is low.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In chemistry, an **alcohol** (from Arabic *al-kuḥl* 'the kohl') is a type of organic compound that carries at least one hydroxyl (−OH) functional group bound to a saturated carbon atom.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols range from the simple, like methanol and ethanol, to complex, like sugar alcohols and cholesterol.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The presence of an OH group strongly modifies the properties of hydrocarbons, conferring hydrophilic (water-attracted) properties.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The OH group provides a site at which many reactions can occur.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The flammable nature of the exhalations of wine was already known to ancient natural philosophers such as Aristotle (384–322 BCE), Theophrastus (c.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] However, this did not immediately lead to the isolation of alcohol, even despite the development of more advanced distillation techniques in second- and third-century Roman Egypt.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] An important recognition, first found in one of the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (ninth century CE), was that by adding salt to boiling wine, which increases the wine's relative volatility, the flammability of the resulting vapors may be enhanced.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In the twelfth century, recipes for the production of *aqua ardens* ("burning water", i.e., alcohol) by distilling wine with salt started to appear in a number of Latin works, and by the end of the thirteenth century, it had become a widely known substance among Western European chemists.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still, by which an alcohol purity of 90% could be obtained.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The medicinal properties of ethanol were studied by Arnald of Villanova (1240–1311 CE) and John of Rupescissa (c.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] 1310–1366), the latter of whom regarded it as a life-preserving substance able to prevent all diseases (the *aqua vitae* or "water of life", also called by John the *quintessence* of wine).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The word "alcohol" derives from the Arabic *kohl* (Arabic: الكحل, romanized: *al-kuḥl*), a powder used as an eyeliner.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The first part of the word (*al-*) is the Arabic definite article, equivalent to *the* in English.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The second part of the word (*kuḥl*) has several antecedents in Semitic languages, ultimately deriving from the Akkadian 𒎎𒋆𒁉𒍣𒁕 (*guḫlum*), meaning stibnite or antimony.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Like its antecedents in Arabic and older languages, the term *alcohol* was originally used for the very fine powder produced by the sublimation of the natural mineral stibnite to form antimony trisulfide Sb2S3.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] It was considered to be the essence or "spirit" of this mineral.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] It was used as an antiseptic, eyeliner, and cosmetic.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Later the meaning of alcohol was extended to distilled substances in general, and then narrowed again to ethanol, when "spirits" was a synonym for hard liquor.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Paracelsus and Libavius both used the term *alcohol* to denote a fine powder, the latter speaking of an *alcohol* derived from antimony.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] At the same time Paracelsus uses the word for a volatile liquid; *alcool* or *alcool vini* occurs often in his writings.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The 1657 *Lexicon Chymicum* by William Johnson glosses the word as "antimonium sive stibium." By extension, the word came to refer to any fluid obtained by distillation, including "alcohol of wine," the distilled essence of wine.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Libavius in *Alchymia* (1594) refers to "vini alcohol vel vinum alcalisatum".
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The term *ethanol* was invented in 1892, blending "ethane" with the "-ol" ending of "alcohol", which was generalized as a libfix.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The term *alcohol* originally referred to the primary alcohol ethanol (ethyl alcohol), which is used as a drug and is the main alcohol present in alcoholic drinks.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* appears in the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) chemical name of all substances where the hydroxyl group is the functional group with the highest priority.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] When a higher priority group is present in the compound, the prefix *hydroxy-* is used in its IUPAC name.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* in non-IUPAC names (such as paracetamol or cholesterol) also typically indicates that the substance is an alcohol.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] However, some compounds that contain hydroxyl functional groups have *trivial names* that do not include the suffix *-ol* or the prefix *hydroxy-*, e.g. the sugars glucose and sucrose.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] IUPAC nomenclature is used in scientific publications, and in writings where precise identification of the substance is important.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In naming simple alcohols, the name of the alkane chain loses the terminal *e* and adds the suffix *-ol*, *e.g.*, as in "ethanol" from the alkane chain name "ethane".
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] When necessary, the position of the hydroxyl group is indicated by a number between the alkane name and the *-ol*: propan-1-ol for CH3CH2CH2OH, propan-2-ol for CH3CH(OH)CH3.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] If a higher priority group is present (such as an aldehyde, ketone, or carboxylic acid), then the prefix *hydroxy-*is used, e.g., as in 1-hydroxy-2-propanone (CH3C(O)CH2OH).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Compounds having more than one hydroxy group are called polyols.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] They are named using suffixes -diol, -triol, etc., following a list of the position numbers of the hydroxyl groups, as in propane-1,2-diol for CH3CH(OH)CH2OH (propylene glycol).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In cases where the hydroxy group is bonded to an sp2 carbon on an aromatic ring, the molecule is classified separately as a phenol and is named using the IUPAC rules for naming phenols.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Phenols have distinct properties and are not classified as alcohols.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In other less formal contexts, an alcohol is often called with the name of the corresponding alkyl group followed by the word "alcohol", e.g., methyl alcohol, ethyl alcohol.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Propyl alcohol may be *n*-propyl alcohol or isopropyl alcohol, depending on whether the hydroxyl group is bonded to the end or middle carbon on the straight propane chain.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] As described under systematic naming, if another group on the molecule takes priority, the alcohol moiety is often indicated using the "hydroxy-" prefix.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In archaic nomenclature, alcohols can be named as derivatives of methanol using "-carbinol" as the ending.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] For instance, (CH3)3COH can be named trimethylcarbinol.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols are then classified into primary, secondary (*sec-*, *s-*), and tertiary (*tert-*, *t-*), based upon the number of carbon atoms connected to the carbon atom that bears the hydroxyl functional group.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The respective numeric shorthands 1°, 2°, and 3° are sometimes used in informal settings.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The primary alcohols have general formulas RCH2OH.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest primary alcohol is methanol (CH3OH), for which R = H, and the next is ethanol, for which R = CH3, the methyl group.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary alcohols are those of the form RR'CHOH, the simplest of which is 2-propanol (R = R' = CH3).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] For the tertiary alcohols, the general form is RR'R"COH.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest example is *tert*-butanol (2-methylpropan-2-ol), for which each of R, R', and R" is CH3.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In these shorthands, R, R', and R" represent substituents, alkyl or other attached, generally organic groups.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols have a long history of myriad uses.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol is the most common industrial alcohol, with about 12 million tons/y produced in 1980.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The combined capacity of the other alcohols is about the same, distributed roughly equally.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] With respect to acute toxicity, simple alcohols have low acute toxicities.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Doses of several milliliters are tolerated.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] For pentanols, hexanols, octanols, and longer alcohols, LD50 range from 2–5 g/kg (rats, oral).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol and ethylene glycol are more toxic than other simple alcohols.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Their metabolism is affected by the presence of ethanol, which has a higher affinity for liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In this way, methanol will be excreted intact in urine.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In general, the hydroxyl group makes alcohols polar.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Those groups can form hydrogen bonds to one another and to most other compounds.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Owing to the presence of the polar OH alcohols are more water-soluble than simple hydrocarbons.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol, ethanol, and propanol are miscible in water.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] 1-Butanol, with a four-carbon chain, is moderately soluble.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Because of hydrogen bonding, alcohols tend to have higher boiling points than comparable hydrocarbons and ethers.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The boiling point of the alcohol ethanol is 78.29 °C, compared to 69 °C for the hydrocarbon hexane, and 34.6 °C for diethyl ether.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols occur widely in nature, as derivatives of glucose such as cellulose and hemicellulose, and in phenols and their derivatives such as lignin.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Starting from biomass, 180 billion tons/y of complex carbohydrates (sugar polymers) are produced commercially (as of 2014).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Many other alcohols are pervasive in organisms, as manifested in other sugars such as fructose and sucrose, in polyols such as glycerol, and in some amino acids such as serine.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Simple alcohols like methanol, ethanol, and propanol occur in modest quantities in nature, and are industrially synthesized in large quantities for use as chemical precursors, fuels, and solvents.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Many alcohols are produced by hydroxylation, i.e., the installation of a hydroxy group using oxygen or a related oxidant.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Hydroxylation is the means by which the body processes many poisons, converting lipophilic compounds into hydrophilic derivatives that are more readily excreted.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Enzymes called hydroxylases and oxidases facilitate these conversions.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Many industrial alcohols, such as cyclohexanol for the production of nylon, are produced by hydroxylation.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In the Ziegler process, linear alcohols are produced from ethylene and triethylaluminium followed by oxidation and hydrolysis.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The process generates a range of alcohols that are separated by distillation.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Many higher alcohols are produced by hydroformylation of alkenes followed by hydrogenation.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Such processes give fatty alcohols, which are useful for detergents.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Industry produces low-weight molecular alcohols (e.g. ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, and *tert*-butanol) through the acid-catalyzed hydration of alkenes, the latter typically from cracking fractions of distilled crude oil.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Two implementations are employed: the direct and indirect methods.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In the indirect method, the alkene is converted to a sulfate ester, which is subsequently hydrolyzed.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The direct method eschews intermediates, instead using water to quench an intermediate carbocation.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Less aggressive reagents suffice for vicinal difunctionalization.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In industry, the diol ethylene glycol forms when ethylene oxide is hydrolyzed.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In the laboratory, sulfuric acid also catalyzes hydration of alkenes to secondary or tertiary alcohols.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] More controllable net hydrations proceed in multiple steps, with a vicinally-functionalized intermediate.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Thus oxymercuration initially forms an organomercury alcohol, which can then undergo reductive demetalation; and alkenes react with *N*-bromosuccinimide and water to form halohydrins.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In hydroboration-oxidation and the related Mukaiyama hydration, an alkene is hydrometalated, then oxidized.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Ethanol is obtained by fermentation of glucose (which is often obtained from starch) in the presence of yeast.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Like ethanol, butanol can be produced by fermentation processes.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] *Saccharomyces* yeast are known to produce these higher alcohols at temperatures above 75 °F (24 °C).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The bacterium *Clostridium acetobutylicum* can feed on cellulose (also an alcohol) to produce butanol on an industrial scale.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alkyl halides react with aqueous NaOH or KOH to give alcohols in nucleophilic aliphatic substitution.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary and especially tertiary alkyl halides will give the elimination (alkene) product instead.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Grignard reagents react with carbonyl groups to give secondary and tertiary alcohols.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Related reactions are the Barbier reaction and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Aldehydes or ketones are reduced with sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride (after an acidic workup).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Another reduction using aluminium isopropoxide is the Meerwein–Ponndorf–Verley reduction.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation is the asymmetric reduction of β-keto-esters.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] With aqueous p*K*a values of around 16–19, alcohols are, in general, slightly weaker acids than water.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] With strong bases such as sodium hydride or sodium they form salts called *alkoxides*, with the general formula RO−M+ (where R is an alkyl and M is a metal).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The acidity of alcohols is strongly affected by solvation.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In the gas phase, alcohols are more acidic than in water.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In DMSO, alcohols (and water) have a p*K*a of around 29–32.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] As a consequence, alkoxides (and hydroxide) are powerful bases and nucleophiles (e.g., for the Williamson ether synthesis) in this solvent.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In particular, RO− or HO− in DMSO can be used to generate significant equilibrium concentrations of acetylide ions through the deprotonation of alkynes (see Favorskii reaction).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with hydrochloric acid to produce tertiary alkyl chloride.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Primary and secondary alcohols are converted to the corresponding chlorides using thionyl chloride and various phosphorus chloride reagents.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] In the Barton–McCombie deoxygenation an alcohol is deoxygenated to an alkane with tributyltin hydride or a trimethylborane-water complex in a radical substitution reaction.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Meanwhile, the oxygen atom has lone pairs of nonbonded electrons that render it weakly basic in the presence of strong acids such as sulfuric acid.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Upon treatment with strong acids, alcohols undergo the E1 elimination reaction to produce alkenes.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction, in general, obeys Zaytsev's rule, which states that the most stable (usually the most substituted) alkene is formed.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols are eliminated easily at just above room temperature, but primary alcohols require a higher temperature.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] A more controlled elimination reaction requires the formation of the xanthate ester.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with strong acids to generate carbocations.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction is related to their dehydration, e.g. isobutylene from *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] A special kind of dehydration reaction involves triphenylmethanol and especially its amine-substituted derivatives.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] When treated with acid, these alcohols lose water to give stable carbocations, which are commercial dyes.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohol and carboxylic acids react in the so-called Fischer esterification.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Other types of ester are prepared in a similar manner−for example, tosyl (tosylate) esters are made by reaction of the alcohol with 4-toluenesulfonyl chloride in pyridine.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alcohols (R−CH2OH) can be oxidized either to aldehydes (R−CHO) or to carboxylic acids (R−CO2H).
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The oxidation of secondary alcohols (R1R2CH−OH) normally terminates at the ketone (R1R2C=O) stage.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols (R1R2R3C−OH) are resistant to oxidation.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids normally proceeds via the corresponding aldehyde, which is transformed via an *aldehyde hydrate* (R−CH(OH)2) by reaction with water before it can be further oxidized to the carboxylic acid.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] Reagents useful for the transformation of primary alcohols to aldehydes are normally also suitable for the oxidation of secondary alcohols to ketones.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] These include Collins reagent and Dess–Martin periodinane.
[src:lanolin/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids can be carried out using potassium permanganate or the Jones reagent.
[src:lanolin/alkoxylation] Another industrially significant epoxide is propylene oxide (PO, OCH2CHCH3).
[src:lanolin/alkoxylation] PO is mainly used for alkoxylation to produce polyether polyols.
[src:lanolin/alkoxylation] Polyols derived from PO have complex stereochemistry owing to the chirality of the propylene oxide.
[src:lanolin/alkoxylation] These polyols are used on a large scale to produce polyurethanes, by condensation with diisocyanates.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] α-Hydroxy acids are stronger acids compared to their non-alpha hydroxy counterparts, a property enhanced by internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] AHAs serve a dual purpose: industrially, they are utilized as additives in animal feed and as precursors for polymer synthesis.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] In cosmetics, they are commonly used for their ability to chemically exfoliate the skin.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Aldonic acids, a type of sugar acid, are a class of naturally occurring hydroxycarboxylic acids.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] They have the general chemical formula, HO2C(CHOH)*n*CH2OH.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Gluconic acid, a particularly common aldonic acid, the oxidized derivative of glucose.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] 2-Hydroxy-4-(methylthio)butyric acid is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of 3-dimethylsulfoniopropionate, precursor to natural dimethyl sulfide.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] One common synthesis hydrolyzes the relatively common α-halocarboxylic acids to produce 2-hydroxycarboxylic acids.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Further specialized synthetic routes are the reaction of dilithiated carboxylic acids with oxygen, followed by neutralization...
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] The synthesis and utilization of polymers based on lactic acid, including polylactic acid (PLA) and its cyclic ester lactide, are used in the creation of biodegradable materials such as medical implants, drug delivery systems, and sutures.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Similarly, glycolic acid serves as a foundation for the development of poly(glycolic acid), spelled polyglycolide (PGA), a polymer distinguished by its high crystallinity, thermal stability, and mechanical strength, despite its synthetic origins.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Both PLA and PGA are fully biodegradable.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Furthermore, mandelic acid, another alpha hydroxy acid, when combined with sulfuric acid produces "SAMMA", obtained via condensation with sulfuric acid.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Early laboratory work performed in 2002 and 2007 against notable pathogens such as the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the herpes simplex virus (HSV) suggest SAMMA warrants further investigation as a topical microbicide to prevent vaginal sexually-transmitted infection transmission.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] 2-Hydroxy-4-(methylthio)butyric acid, alpha hydroxy carboxylic acid, is used commercially in a racemic mixture to substitute for methionine in animal feed.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] α-Hydroxy acids, such as glycolic acid, lactic acid, citric acid, and mandelic acid, serve as precursors in organic synthesis, playing a role in the industrial-scale preparation of various compounds.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] These acids are used when synthesizing aldehydes through oxidative cleavage. α-Hydroxy acids are particularly prone to acid-catalyzed decarbonylation, yielding carbon monoxide, a ketone or aldehyde, and water as by-products.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Alpha hydroxy acids are generally safe when used on the skin as a cosmetic agent using the recommended dosage.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] The most common side-effects are mild skin irritations, redness and flaking.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] The United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and Cosmetic Ingredient Review expert panels both suggest that alpha hydroxy acids are safe to use as long as they are sold at low concentrations, pH levels greater than 3.5, and include thorough safety instructions.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] The FDA has warned consumers that care should be taken when using alpha hydroxy acids after an industry-sponsored study found that they can increase the likelihood of sunburns.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] This effect is reversible after stopping the use of alpha hydroxy acids.
[src:lanolin/alpha-hydroxy-acid] Other sources suggest that glycolic acid, in particular, may protect from sun damage.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:lanolin/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Anti-personnel shells are designed to fragment into many pieces and can affect a large area.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Armor-piercing rounds are specially hardened to penetrate armor, while smoke ammunition creates a fog that screens people from view.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] More generic ammunition (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) can often be modified slightly to achieve a more specific effect (e.g., tracer, incendiary), whilst larger explosive rounds can be altered by using different fuzes.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The term *fuze* refers to the detonator of an explosive round or shell.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The spelling is different in British English and American English (fuse/fuze respectively), and they are unrelated to a fuse (electrical).
[src:lanolin/ammunition] A fuse was earlier used to ignite the propellant (e.g., such as on a firework) until the advent of more reliable systems, such as the primer or igniter that is used in most modern ammunition.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The fuze of a weapon can be used to alter how the ammunition works.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] These allow a single ammunition type to be altered to suit the situation it is required for.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] There are many fuze designs, ranging from simple mechanical to complex radar- and barometric-based systems.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Fuzes are typically armed by the acceleration force of firing the projectile and are armed several meters after clearing the weapon's bore.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] This helps to ensure the ammunition is safer to handle when loading into the weapon and reduces the chance of the detonator firing before the ammunition has cleared the weapon.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The propellant is the component of ammunition that is activated inside the weapon and provides the kinetic energy required to move the projectile from the weapon to the target.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] In recent years, compressed gas, magnetic energy, and electrical energy have been used as propellants.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Until the 20th century, gunpowder was the most common propellant in ammunition.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] However, it has since been replaced by a wide range of fast-burning compounds that are more reliable and efficient.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The propellant charge is distinct from the projectile charge, which is activated by the fuze, which causes the ammunition effect (e.g., the exploding of an artillery round).
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The cartridge is the container that holds the projectile and propellant.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Not all ammunition types have a cartridge case.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] In its place, a wide range of materials can be used to contain the explosives and parts.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] With some large weapons, the ammunition components are stored separately until loaded into the weapon system for firing.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] With small arms, caseless ammunition can reduce the weight and cost of ammunition and simplify the firing process, increasing the firing rate, but the technology is still maturing and has functional issues.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The projectile is the part of the ammunition that leaves the weapon and affects the target.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] This effect is usually either kinetic (e.g., as with a standard bullet) or explosive.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] An ammunition dump is a military facility for storing live ammunition and explosives to be distributed and used at a later date.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Such a storage facility is extremely hazardous, with a high risk of accidents during unloading, packing, and transferring the ammunition.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] In the event of a fire or explosion, the site and its surrounding area are immediately evacuated, and the stored ammunition is left to detonate completely, with limited firefighting attempts from a safe distance.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] In large facilities, there may be a flooding system to extinguish a fire or prevent an explosion automatically.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Typically, an ammunition dump will have a large buffer zone surrounding it to avoid casualties in the event of an accident.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] There will also be perimeter security measures in place to prevent unauthorized personnel from accessing the area and to guard against potential threats from enemy forces.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] A magazine is a place where a quantity of ammunition or other explosive material is stored temporarily before being used.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The term may be used for a facility that stores large quantities of ammunition, although this is normally referred to as an ammunition dump.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Magazines are typically located in the field for quick access when engaging the enemy.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The ammunition storage area on a warship is referred to as the "ship's magazine".
[src:lanolin/ammunition] On a smaller scale, magazine is also the name given to the ammunition storage and feeding device of a repeating firearm.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Gunpowder must be stored in a dry place (stable room temperature) to keep it usable for at least 10 years.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] It is also recommended to avoid hot places, because friction or heat might ignite a spark and cause an explosion.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The standard weapon of a modern soldier is an assault rifle, which, like other small arms, uses cartridge ammunition sized for the weapon.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Ammunition is carried on the person in box magazines specific to the weapon, ammunition boxes, pouches, or bandoliers.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The amount of ammunition carried depends on the soldier's strength, the expected action required, and the ammunition's ability to move through the logistical chain to replenish the supply.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] A soldier may also carry a smaller amount of specialized ammunition for heavier weapons, such as machine guns and mortars, thereby spreading the burden of squad weapons among many people.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Too little ammunition threatens the mission, while too much limits the soldier's mobility and also threatens the mission.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] A shell is a payload-carrying projectile which, as opposed to a shot, contains explosives or other fillings, in use since the 19th century.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Artillery shells are ammunition that is designed to be fired from artillery, which has an effect over long distances, usually indirectly (i.e., out of sight of the target).
[src:lanolin/ammunition] There are many different types of artillery ammunition, but they are usually high-explosive and designed to shatter into fragments on impact to maximize damage.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The fuze on an artillery shell can alter how it explodes or behaves, giving it a more specialized effect.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Common types of artillery ammunition include high explosive, smoke, illumination, and practice rounds.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Some artillery rounds are designed as cluster munitions.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Artillery ammunition will almost always include a projectile (the only exception being demonstration or blank rounds), fuze, and propellant of some form.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] When a cartridge case is not used, another method of containing the propellant bags is used, usually in a breech-loading weapon; see Breechloader.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Tank ammunition was developed in World War I as tanks first appeared on the battlefield.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The development of shaped charges has had a significant impact on anti-tank ammunition design, now common in both tank-fired ammunition and in anti-tank missiles, including anti-tank guided missiles.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Naval weapons were originally the same as many land-based weapons, but the ammunition was designed for specific use, such as a solid shot designed to hole an enemy ship and chain-shot to cut rigging and sails.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Modern naval engagements have occurred over far longer distances than historic battles, so as ship armor has increased in strength and thickness, the ammunition to defeat it has also changed.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Naval ammunition is now designed to reach very high velocities (to improve its armor-piercing abilities) and may have specialized fuzes to defeat specific types of vessels.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] However, due to the extended ranges at which modern naval combat may occur, guided missiles have largely supplanted guns and shells.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] With every successive improvement in military arms, a corresponding change has occurred in the method of supplying ammunition in the required quantities.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] As soon as projectiles were required (such as javelins and arrows), there needed to be a method of replenishment.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] When non-specialized, interchangeable, or recoverable ammunition was used (e.g., arrows), it was possible to pick up spent arrows (both friendly and enemy) and reuse them.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] However, with the advent of explosive or non-recoverable ammunition, this was no longer possible, and new ammunition supplies would be needed.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The weight of ammunition required, particularly for artillery shells, can be considerable, necessitating extra time to replenish supplies.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] In modern times, there has been an increase in the standardization of many ammunition types among allies (e.g., the NATO Standardization Agreement) that has enabled the sharing of ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO).
[src:lanolin/ammunition] As of 2013, lead-based ammunition production is the second-largest annual use of lead in the US, accounting for over 60,000 metric tons consumed in 2012.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in a carcass or body that was never retrieved can enter environmental systems and become toxic to wildlife.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] The US military has experimented with replacing lead with copper as a slug in their green bullets which reduces the dangers posed by lead in the environment as a result of artillery.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Since 2010, this has eliminated over 2000 tons of lead in waste streams.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Hunters are also encouraged to use monolithic bullets, which exclude any lead content.
[src:lanolin/ammunition] Unexploded ammunition can remain active for a very long time and poses a significant threat to both humans and the environment.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin in nature protects wool and skin from climate and the environment; it is also involved in skin (integumental) hygiene.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin and its derivatives are used in the protection, treatment, and beautification of human skin.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] A typical high-purity grade of lanolin is composed predominantly of long chain waxy esters (approximately 97% by weight) with the remainder being lanolin alcohols, lanolin acids and lanolin hydrocarbons.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] An estimated 8,000 to 20,000 different types of lanolin esters are present in lanolin, resulting from combinations between the different lanolin acids and alcohols; about 200 acids and 100 alcohols had been identified by 1986.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] In addition to being useful itself, lanolin's complex composition of long-chain esters, hydroxyesters, diesters, lanolin alcohols, and lanolin acids makes it a starting point for the production of a whole spectrum of lanolin derivatives with wide-ranging chemical and physical properties.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The main derivatisation routes include hydrolysis, fractional solvent crystallisation, esterification, hydrogenation, alkoxylation and quaternisation.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin derivatives obtained from these processes are used widely in both cosmetics and skin treatment products.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Hydrolysis of lanolin yields lanolin alcohols and lanolin acids.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin alcohols are a rich source of cholesterol, an important skin lipid, and are powerful water-in-oil emulsifiers; they have been used extensively in skincare products for over 100 years.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Approximately 40% of the acids derived from lanolin are alpha-hydroxy acids (AHAs).
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The use of AHAs in skin care products has attracted much attention.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Details of the AHAs isolated from lanolin can be seen in the table below.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Crude lanolin constitutes about 5–25% of the weight of freshly shorn wool.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Wool from one Merino sheep produces about 250–300 ml (9–11 imp fl oz; 8–10 US fl oz) of recoverable wool grease.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is extracted by washing the wool in hot water with a special wool-scouring detergent to remove dirt, wool grease (crude lanolin), suint (sweat salts), and anything else stuck to the wool.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The wool grease is continuously removed during this washing process by centrifuge separators, which concentrate it into a waxlike substance which melts at approximately 38 °C (100 °F).
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin and its many derivatives are used extensively both for personal care (e.g. cosmetics, facial cosmetics, lip products) and healthcare (topical liniments).
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is also used in lubricants, rust-preventive coatings, shoe polish, and other commercial products.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is a relatively common allergen, causing what is often misunderstood as a wool allergy.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] However, allergy to a lanolin-containing product is difficult to pinpoint, and often different forms of lanolin may not cause an allergic reaction in the same person.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Patch testing can be done if a lanolin allergy is suspected.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] It is frequently used in protective baby skin treatment.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] It is also used for sore nipples from breastfeeding, but health authorities recommend alternative methods first, including nipple cleaning, improving baby positioning, and ultimately expressing milk by hand.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is reported to have soothing properties, but there is a lack of research.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is used commercially in many industrial products ranging from rust-proof coatings to lubricants.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Some sailors use lanolin to create slippery surfaces on their propellers and stern gear to which barnacles cannot adhere.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanocote) containing up to 85% lanolin are used to prevent corrosion in marine fasteners, especially when two different metals are in contact with each other in the presence of saltwater.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The water-repellent properties make it valuable in many applications as a lubricant grease where corrosion would otherwise be a problem.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] 7-Dehydrocholesterol from lanolin is used as a raw material for producing vitamin D3 by irradiation with ultraviolet light.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Baseball players often use it to soften and break in their baseball gloves—shaving cream with lanolin is popularly used for this.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Anhydrous liquid lanolin, combined with parabens, has been used in trials as artificial tears to treat dry eye.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Anhydrous lanolin is also used as a lubricant for brass musical instrument tuning slides.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin can also be applied to woollen garments to make them water- and dirt-repellent, such as for cloth diaper covers.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is used in lip balm products such as Carmex.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] It can irritate the lips of some people.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is sometimes used by people on continuous positive airway pressure therapy to reduce irritation with masks, particularly nasal pillow masks that often create sore spots in the nostrils.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is a popular additive to moustache wax, particularly 'extra-firm' varieties.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is used as a primary lubricating component in aerosol-based brass lubricants when reloading ammunition.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] It is mixed warm 1:12 with ethanol, usually about 99% pure, which acts as a carrier which evaporates quickly after application, leaving a thin film of lanolin which protects against brass seizing in resizing dies.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is used as a lubricant for leather and fur, and in polishes and protective coatings for shoes and leather goods.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin, when mixed with ingredients such as neatsfoot oil, beeswax and glycerol, is used in various leather treatments, for example in some saddle soaps and in leather care products.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] In addition to general purity requirements, in the US lanolin must meet official requirements for permissible levels of pesticide residues.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The Fifth Supplement of the United States Pharmacopoeia XXII published in 1992 was the first to specify limits for 34 named pesticides.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] 40 mg/kg) total pesticides was stipulated for lanolin of general use, with no more than 10 ppm of any individual pesticide.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] A second monograph also introduced into the US Pharmacopoeia XXII in 1992 was entitled 'Modified Lanolin'.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin conforming to this monograph is intended for use in more exacting applications, for example on open wounds.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] In this monograph, the limit of total pesticides was reduced to 3 ppm total pesticides, with none present at over 1 ppm.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] In 2000, the European Pharmacopoeia introduced pesticide residue limits into its lanolin monograph.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] This requirement, which is generally regarded as the new quality standard, extends the list of pesticides to 40, and imposes even lower concentration limits.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Some very high-purity grades of lanolin surpass monograph requirements.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] New products obtained using complex purification techniques produce lanolin esters in their natural state, removing oxidative and environmental impurities resulting in white, odourless, hypoallergenic lanolin.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] These ultra-high-purity grades of lanolin are ideally suited to the treatment of dermatological disorders such as eczema and on open wounds.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin attracted attention owing to a misunderstanding concerning its sensitising potential.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] A study carried out at New York University Hospital in the early 1950s had shown that about 1% of patients with dermatological disorders were allergic to the lanolin used at the time.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] By one estimate, not differentiating between the general healthy population and patients with dermatological disorders exaggerated the sensitising potential of lanolin by 5,000–6,000 times.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The European Cosmetics Directive, introduced in July 1976, contained a stipulation that cosmetics which contained lanolin should be labelled to that effect.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] This ruling was challenged immediately, and in the early 1980s, it was overturned and removed from the directive.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Despite only being in force for a short period of time, this ruling did harm both to the lanolin industry and to the reputation of lanolin in general.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The Cosmetics Directive ruling only applied to cosmetics, not to the many hundreds of lanolin's different uses in dermatological products for the treatment of compromised skin conditions.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Modern analytical methods have revealed lanolin possesses a number of important chemical and physical similarities to human stratum corneum lipids; the lipids which help regulate the rate of water loss across the epidermis and govern the hydration state of the skin.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Cryogenic scanning electron microscopy has shown that lanolin, like human stratum corneum lipids, consists of a mass of liquid crystalline material.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Cross-polarised light microscopy has shown the multilamellar vesicles formed by lanolin are identical to those formed by human stratum corneum lipids.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The incorporation of bound water into the stratum corneum involves the formation of multilamellar vesicles.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Skin bioengineering studies have shown the duration of the emollient (skin smoothing) action produced by lanolin is very significant, and lasts for many hours.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin applied to the skin at 2 mg/cm2 has been shown to reduce roughness by about 35% after one hour and 50% after two hours, with the overall effect lasting for considerably more than eight hours.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin is also known to form semiocclusive (breathable) films on the skin.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] When applied daily at around 4 mg/cm2 for five consecutive days, the positive moisturizing effects of lanolin were detectable until 72 hours after final application.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] Lanolin may achieve some of its moisturizing effects by forming a secondary moisture reservoir within the skin.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] The barrier repair properties of lanolin have been reported to be superior to those produced by both petrolatum and glycerol.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] In a small clinical study conducted on volunteer subjects with very dry (xerotic) hands, lanolin was shown to be superior to petrolatum in reducing the signs and symptoms of dryness and scaling, cracks and abrasions, and pain and itch.
[src:lanolin/lanolin] In another study, a high-purity grade of lanolin was found to be significantly superior to petrolatum in assisting the healing of superficial wounds.
